  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 18.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "By the good hand of our God upon us.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " This is Ezra's usual mode of acknowledging the good providence and favour of Almighty God (see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezra 7:6, 9, 27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezra 8:31",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Similar expressions occur also in Nehemiah (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Nehemiah 2:8, 18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), but not elsewhere in Scripture. A ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "man of understanding.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " In the Hebrew ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Ish-sekel",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", which some take for a proper name, but without any necessity. No such name is known to have existed; and the real name of \"the man of understanding\" appears to have been \"Sherebiah,\" who is mentioned more than once in Nehemiah (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Nehemiah 8:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Nehemiah 9:4, 5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") as a chief Levite. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And Sherebiah",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " should be simply \"Sherebiah.\" The preposition \"and\" (Hebrew ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "ן",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") has been inserted by a careless copyist. Ezra 8:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The delegates sent to Iddo succeeded, through the gracious assistance of God (אל בּיד, see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezra 7:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), in inducing forty Levites, and two hundred and twenty Nethinim, by means of Iddo's influence, to join their fellow-countrymen in their journey to Jerusalem. They brought to us ... לנוּ and עלינוּ refer to Ezra and his fellow-travellers. שׂכל אישׁ, a man of understanding, seems to be a proper name, being joined to Sherebiah, the name following, by a ו copulative. He was one of the descendants of Mahli, the son, i.e., grandson, of Levi the son of Israel, i.e., Jacob: comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 6:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 6:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
